title Reviving replaces renaming — a new active-reviving sibling to active-designing
prompt Keaton proposed, instead of renaming, a "reviving" concept where we rewrite what we need to fit the new Glow direction, with active-reviving evolving next to active-designing.
think This is a genuinely better resolution than the role-map alone, and I said so honestly rather than just agreeing. The insight that makes it work: a revival is a NEW artifact grown beside the elder, so it can be born with its Glow-direction name from the start — which means renaming is never needed. The elder keeps its name and green witnesses; the revival supersedes it only when proven.
think Recognized this names a pattern the project already lives by, so it is discovery, not invention: Pond revived ai-jail and superseded it on word; Rye is a thin frontend grown beside Zig's std; Neth revives the retired WOV-TigerBeetle pin. Reviving gives that activity a name and a folder rather than introducing something foreign.
think Drew the sibling distinction sharply so active-reviving is not a redundant folder: active-designing plans something NEW with no required ancestor; active-reviving re-grows something that EXISTS, always naming its elder, backward-rooted and forward-growing. If a brief has no ancestor, it is designing; if it rewrites a real working thing into Glow, it is reviving.
think Gave reviving five disciplines, each mapped to a law already kept: name the elder; grow beside never break; born with its Glow name; supersede only when proven (Pond pattern); may shelter in Maze. This makes it rigorous rather than a vibe.
think Seated the concept as superseding the earlier "mass rename deferred, cheapest-first" framing from the umbrella and naming-decisions specs — there is no mass rename in this project's future; where those specs say "rename deferred," read "revived when next re-grown in Glow." The role map still stands; reviving is simply HOW a module comes to carry its Glow name, by rebirth not relabel. Left the older dated specs as record and let the new spec carry the supersession, per the project's own marker discipline, rather than churning older bodies.
obs The three ideas now compose cleanly: the role map is what each module is in the pitch today (zero cost); reviving is the process of re-growing it into Glow over time as a new named artifact; Maze is where an in-progress revival shelters until it graduates. Pitch in Urbit roles now, revive into Glow one proven artifact at a time, never rename anything.
file active-reviving/README.md why: the living home and index for revivals in motion (Neth, the doc pipeline, Glow itself, Pond as precedent)
file context/specs/20260714-004428_reviving-replaces-renaming.md why: seats reviving as a first-class concept and retires the mass-rename framing
file ORGANIZING.md why: names active-reviving/ as a sibling to active-designing/
file .gitignore why: allow-lists /active-reviving/
recommend keep-going — this is an additive organizing concept that reduces future churn and needs no migration; a natural next step is Keaton picking one revival (Neth's minimal root witness is the readiest) to move from active-reviving design into a first landed artifact.
